# performing forward selection
names <- colnames(user_training_data |> select(-UNS))
accuracies <- tibble(size = integer(), 
                     model_string = character(), 
                     accuracy = numeric())

knn_spec <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", 
                             neighbors = tune()) |>
     set_engine("kknn") |>
     set_mode("classification")

cancer_vfold <- vfold_cv(user_training_data, v = 5, strata = UNS)

n_total <- length(names)

selected <- c()

for (i in 1:n_total) {
    accs <- list()
    models <- list()
    for (j in 1:length(names)) {
        preds_new <- c(selected, names[[j]])
        model_string <- paste("UNS", "~", paste(preds_new, collapse="+"))

        # create a recipe from the model string
        cancer_recipe <- recipe(as.formula(model_string), 
                                data = user_training_data) |>
                          step_scale(all_predictors()) |>
                          step_center(all_predictors())

        # tune the KNN classifier with these predictors, 
        # and collect the accuracy for the best K
        acc <- workflow() |>
          add_recipe(cancer_recipe) |>
          add_model(knn_spec) |>
          tune_grid(resamples = cancer_vfold, grid = 10) |>
          collect_metrics() |>
          filter(.metric == "accuracy") |>
          summarize(mx = max(mean))
        acc <- acc$mx |> unlist()

        # add this result to the dataframe
        accs[[j]] <- acc
        models[[j]] <- model_string
    }
    jstar <- which.max(unlist(accs))
    accuracies <- accuracies |> 
      add_row(size = i, 
              model_string = models[[jstar]], 
              accuracy = accs[[jstar]])
    selected <- c(selected, names[[jstar]])
    names <- names[-jstar]
}

Introduction¶

Which set of predictors accurately demonstrates one’s UNS: The Knowledge Level of a User?¶

For our group project we will explore the development of intuitive knowledge classifiers and the modeling of domain dependent data. The dataset aims to classify the level of a user's knowledge on Electrical DC Machines, using an intuitive algorithmic classifier. We will use supervised learning techniques to analyze the dataset and build a predictive model that can identify the user's knowledge level. We will also evaluate the performance of the classifier based on the accuracy of predictions and the amount of training data needed. First, the proposed knowledge classifier investigates the best-weighted values for the students knowledge classes. Then, the distance between the students is calculated using their data and weight values. These differences in the classification procedure are then employed to define their knowledge class (very_low, Low, Middle, High). The students are classified into their respective knowledge classes and the model groups them by weighting students domain-dependent data, a combination of user modeling algorithms, and a population-based approach. The approach enables us to optimize the accuracy score and visualize the relationship between the categories.

Method¶

Given that the preidcted variable (UNS) is categorical and not continuous, it is most suitable to use a classification model. Therefore, we are going to use the K-nearest neighbors classification model to predict the UNS classes.

Data wrangling¶

The UNS classes in the train and test dataset are labeled differently. One was very_low, while the other was Very Low. To deal with this anomaly, we reformatted the UNS label in the training set to Very Low. This keeps the format consistent across the entire class, and avoid potential issues with classification and predictions.

Performing data analysis¶

The predictor variables we are going to use are PEG and LPR. This is because we used forward selection to try and see which combination of variables is most likely to be accurate for predicting UNS, and PEG + LPR had the highest estimated accuracy, at 0.96. We also graphs PEG against LPR and coloured the observations by UNS, to try and see if the observations are indeed separated into clear categories, which they are.

We first created a recipe with our training data and tuned the number of neighbors using K-NN classification. We then performed a 5-fold cross-validation in order to find the most accurate k-value for our model using the training data. We created a workflow using our recipe and 5-folds to tune the model to choose the most accurate K-values. We used collect_metrics to find the accuracy of each classifier and plotted the accuracies on a line plot to get the k-value with the highest estimated accuracy.

In [18]:
set.seed(2022)
knn_spec <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = tune()) |>
      set_engine("kknn") |>
      set_mode("classification")

knn_recipe <- recipe(UNS ~ PEG + LPR, data = user_training_data)

vfold <- vfold_cv(user_training_data, v = 5, strata = UNS)

knn_fit <- workflow() |>
              add_recipe(knn_recipe) |>
              add_model(knn_spec) |>
              tune_grid(resamples = vfold, grid = 10) |>
              collect_metrics() |>
              filter(.metric == "accuracy")

knn_fit_graph <- ggplot(knn_fit, aes(x = neighbors, y = mean)) +
                geom_point() +
                geom_line() +
                labs(x = "Neighbors (K)", y = "Accuracy Estimate") +
                ggtitle("Plotting Accuracy Estimate against Neighbor K") +
                theme(text = element_text(size = 14))

Choosing a higher estimated accuracy gives us a higher chance of creating a more accurate model. As we can see from the accuracy estimate and K-nearest neighbor plot in Figure 7., the K-value of 3, 5, and 6, all have very similarly high accuracy values. However, we chose k = 3, because it is more time efficient to choose a smaller k-value where possible. This is because as the k value increases, the time used for processing also increases.

After finding the optimal k value, we create a workflow that would predict the data against our testing set. knn_spec <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = 3) |>
      set_engine("kknn") |>
      set_mode("classification")

user_fit <- workflow() |>
              add_recipe(knn_recipe) |>
              add_model(knn_spec) |>
              fit(data = user_training_data)

class_prediction <- predict(user_fit, user_test_data) |>
              bind_cols(user_test_data)

Disucssion¶

In our analysis, we found that our classifier predicted high UNS scores when PEG was approximately 0.75 or higher and middle UNS scores when PEG was between 0.5 and 0.75. For PEG between about 0.25 and 0.5 the classifier predicted UNS to be low and for PEG less than 0.25 the UNS was very low. It appears that our model was able to perform effectively in classifying the UNS of users based on PEG and LPR.

Additionally, the accuracy score we got on our testing data was 0.951. While this appears to be good, keep in mind that the training score was 0.957, which is slightly higher than what we have for the test set. Normally, if the train and test scores are significantly different, then our model would be considered overfitting or underfitting. However, the difference is very small, thus indicating that our model was successful in accurately predicting UNS. Therefore, we can use it to analyze the relationship between user knowledge and exam performance.

Expectations¶

This is what we expected to find after running our model on the testing data, as these results are sufficient proof of coherent and logical comprehension of DC machines. Previously, when we plotted the graph of PEG vs. LPR coloured by UNS while doing the preliminary data analysis, we found a trend that higher PEG and LPR led to higher UNS. In addition, it makes logical sense that students who do well on exams pertaining to DC machines and exams on subjects related to DC machines would have a better understanding of DC machines than students who dont. Using their exam grades as a reflection of their knowledge is an adequate observation to base our prediction on.

Impact of findings¶

These findings will allow for data-based evidence on which method would lead to a better understanding of DC machines. We expect to find that higher levels of PEG and LPR will lead to a better understanding of DC machines, ie: a higher UNS. These findings could have a positive impact on the academic community, as we could let professors know how to better gauge their students understanding of a certain topic.

What's next¶

Some further questions we can ask are: How should we optimize the students exam performance with various Goal Objects? What do we need to improve to better teach students about Electrical DC Machines? What are the best methods students can use to improve their understanding?

Conclusion¶

Overall, we used a K-nearest neighbors classification model to determine the relation between PEG and LPR to predict UNS. The chosen predictors led to a good prediction of the student's understanding of DC machines. Our model shows that higher PEG and LPR often leads to a higher UNS value as well. Meanwhile, lower PEG and LPR would lead to a lower UNS value. This finding can help professors measure their students understanding of a certain topic. The next step for us could be focusing on optimizing the student's understanding of DC machines using what we know.
